# import data #####
SIA_SWO  <-  read.table(file = "results_mixsiar_drivers.csv", sep  = ";", header = T) %>% 
  drop_na(cepha)

# Group prey 
prey_grouped <- SIA_SWO %>%
  mutate(
    fish = bathy + gadipela,
    ceph = cepha + cepha2) %>% 
  drop_na(ceph)

1 GAM ranking

# Create a vector of variable names
variables <- c("s(LJFL, k=5)", "s(depth, k=5)", "s(MLD, k=5)", "s(Chlmean, k=5)","s(SST, k=5)","s(fishing_effort, k=5)")

# Generate all possible combinations of variables
combinations <- lapply(1:length(variables), function(x) combn(variables, x, simplify = FALSE))

1.1 Fish

# Initialize a list to store the models
models_fish <- list()

# Create a data frame to store the deviance and AIC values
rank_fish <- data.frame(
  Model = character(),
  Deviance = double(),
  AIC = double()
)

# Fit a GAM for each combination of variables
# run the gams
a=Sys.time()
for (comb in unlist(combinations, recursive = FALSE)) {
  formula_str <- as.formula(paste("fish  ~  te(LON,LAT) +", paste(comb, collapse = " + ")))
  model <- gam(formula_str, data = prey_grouped, family = betar(link = "logit"))
  models_fish[[paste(comb, collapse = ", ")]] <- model
}
Sys.time()-a

# Iterate through models and calculate deviance and AIC
for (model_name in names(models_fish)) {
  model <- models_fish[[model_name]]
  
  # Calculate AIC
  aic <- AIC(model)
  
  # Calculate deviance
  deviance_explained <- summary(model)$dev.expl
  
  # Add the results to the data frame
  rank_fish <- rbind(rank_fish, data.frame(
    Model = paste("fish  ~  te(LON,LAT)  + ", model_name),
    Deviance = deviance_explained,
    AIC = aic
  ))
}

1.4.1.1 Cross validation

validation <-data.frame(
  model = character(),
  aic = double(),
  deviance = double(),
  rmse_mean = double(),
  mape_mean = double(),
  pearson_mean = double())

fish_m <- list(fish_NULL, fish_1, fish_2, fish_3, fish_5)

for(j in fish_m){
  
  print(formula(j))
  rmse <- list()
  mape <- list()
  pear <- list()
  
  # Apply cross-validation:
  set.seed(998)  # For reproducibility
  
  # Split the data into a training set and a test set:
  inTraining <- list()
  training <- list()
  testing <- list()
  k <- 25 
  set.seed(235655)
  set <- sample(1:235465775, 25)
  for(i in 1:k) {
   
    set.seed(set[i])
    inTraining[[i]] <- createDataPartition(prey_grouped$fish, p = .75, list = FALSE)
    training[[i]] <- prey_grouped[ inTraining[[i]],]
    testing[[i]]  <- prey_grouped[-inTraining[[i]],]
  }
  
  fish_train <- list()
  fish_test <- list()
  for(i in 1:k) {
   
    fish_train[[i]] <- gam(formula(j), data=training[[i]], family = betar(link = "logit"))
    fish_test[[i]] <- predict(fish_train[[i]], newdata = testing[[i]], se.fit = TRUE,type = "response")
  }
  
  
  for(i in 1:k) {
   
    rmse[[i]] <- Metrics::rmse(testing[[i]]$fish, fish_test[[i]]$fit)
    mape[[i]] <- Metrics::mape(testing[[i]]$fish, fish_test[[i]]$fit)
    pear[[i]] <- cor(testing[[i]]$fish, as.numeric(fish_test[[i]]$fit), method = "pearson")
  }
  
  # Add the results to the data frame
  validation <- rbind(validation, data.frame(
    model = paste(deparse(j$formula)),
    aic = AIC(j),
    deviance = summary(j)$dev.expl,
    rmse_mean = mean(unlist(rmse)),
    mape_mean = mean(unlist(mape)),
    pearson_mean = mean(unlist(pear))))
}

1.4.2.1 Cross validation

validation <-data.frame(
  model = character(),
  aic = double(),
  deviance = double(),
  rmse_mean = double(),
  mape_mean = double(),
  pearson_mean = double())

ceph_m <- list(ceph, ceph1, ceph2, ceph_null, ceph4, ceph5)

for(j in ceph_m){
  
  print(formula(j))
  rmse <- list()
  mape <- list()
  pear <- list()
  
  # Apply cross-validation:
  set.seed(998)  # For reproducibility
  
  # Split the data into a training set and a test set:
  inTraining <- list()
  training <- list()
  testing <- list()
  k <- 25 
  set.seed(235655)
  set <- sample(1:235465775, 25)
  for(i in 1:k) {
   
    set.seed(set[i])
    inTraining[[i]] <- createDataPartition(prey_grouped$fish, p = .75, list = FALSE)
    training[[i]] <- prey_grouped[ inTraining[[i]],]
    testing[[i]]  <- prey_grouped[-inTraining[[i]],]
  }
  
  fish_train <- list()
  fish_test <- list()
  for(i in 1:k) {
   
    fish_train[[i]] <- gam(formula(j), data=training[[i]], family = betar(link = "logit"))
    fish_test[[i]] <- predict(fish_train[[i]], newdata = testing[[i]], se.fit = TRUE,type = "response")
  }
  
  
  for(i in 1:k) {
    rmse[[i]] <- Metrics::rmse(testing[[i]]$fish, fish_test[[i]]$fit)
    mape[[i]] <- Metrics::mape(testing[[i]]$fish, fish_test[[i]]$fit)
    pear[[i]] <- cor(testing[[i]]$fish, as.numeric(fish_test[[i]]$fit), method = "pearson")
  }
  
  # Add the results to the data frame
  validation <- rbind(validation, data.frame(
    model = paste(deparse(j$formula)),
    aic = as.numeric(AIC(j)),
    deviance = summary(j)$dev.expl,
    rmse_mean = mean(unlist(rmse)),
    mape_mean = mean(unlist(mape)),
    pearson_mean = mean(unlist(pear))))
}

3 Spatial autocorrelation

A common problem in the model that not takes into account the spatial component is the spatial autocorrelation. Let’s verify if our model and predictions have this problem.

The Moran’s I is a measure of spatial autocorrelation–how related the values of a variable are based on the locations where they were measured. The null hypothesis of this test is that there is no spatial autocorrelation. To calculate Moran’s I, we will need to generate a matrix of distance weights. Using the latitude and longitude values:

library(sp)#For Moran test
library(spdep)#For Moran test
## Loading required package: spData
## To access larger datasets in this package, install the spDataLarge
## package with: `install.packages('spDataLarge',
## repos='https://nowosad.github.io/drat/', type='source')`
## Loading required package: sf
## Linking to GEOS 3.11.2, GDAL 3.8.2, PROJ 9.3.1; sf_use_s2() is TRUE
# Convert to spatial points
species_data3=prey_grouped
coordinates(species_data3) <- ~ LON + LAT

# Create k-nearest neighbors
knn_neighbors <- knn2nb(knearneigh(coordinates(species_data3), k=4))
## Warning in knearneigh(coordinates(species_data3), k = 4): knearneigh: identical
## points found
## Warning in knearneigh(coordinates(species_data3), k = 4): knearneigh: kd_tree
## not available for identical points
## Warning in knn2nb(knearneigh(coordinates(species_data3), k = 4)): neighbour
## object has 22 sub-graphs
listw <- nb2listw(knn_neighbors, style = "W")#Here the style  W = row standardized (rows sum to 1)  

# Run Moran's I test 
#we now test the moran test on residuals of the model 
moran.test(residuals(fish), listw=listw)
## 
##  Moran I test under randomisation
## 
## data:  residuals(fish)  
## weights: listw    
## 
## Moran I statistic standard deviate = -1.1361, p-value = 0.8721
## alternative hypothesis: greater
## sample estimates:
## Moran I statistic       Expectation          Variance 
##      -0.049484978      -0.004166667       0.001591035
moran.test(residuals(ceph), listw=listw)
## 
##  Moran I test under randomisation
## 
## data:  residuals(ceph)  
## weights: listw

## Moran I statistic standard deviate = -2.677, p-value = 0.9963
## alternative hypothesis: greater
## sample estimates:
## Moran I statistic       Expectation          Variance 
##      -0.110849540      -0.004166667       0.001588140
moran.test(residuals(gela1), listw=listw)
## 
##  Moran I test under randomisation
## 
## data:  residuals(gela1)  
## weights: listw    
## 
## Moran I statistic standard deviate = -2.1238, p-value = 0.9832
## alternative hypothesis: greater
## sample estimates:
## Moran I statistic       Expectation          Variance 
##      -0.088692350      -0.004166667       0.001583987

Moran’s I Test Results Breakdown

Moran I Statistic: - positive values suggests that similar values (presence) tend to cluster together in space. In other words, areas with high values of presence are more likely to be surrounded by other areas with high presence.

Expectation: - Under the null hypothesis of no spatial autocorrelation, the expected value of Moran’s I is close to zero. A value near zero indicates that, on average, there is no spatial autocorrelation when considering random arrangements of points.

Variance: - This represents the variability of the Moran’s I statistic under the null hypothesis. It is used to assess the significance of the observed statistic.

Standard Deviations: - This value indicates how many standard deviations the observed Moran’s I is away from the expected value. A large value suggests a significant departure from randomness.

P-value: - Low p-value indicate that the result is highly significant. It means that there is strong evidence against the null hypothesis of no spatial autocorrelation. You can confidently conclude that there is a significant positive spatial correlation in your data.

Summary: Overall, these results suggest to accept the null hypothesis of no spatial autocorrelation
